{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_26","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,220p' references_cache/PMID_16785429.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nreference_id: PMID:16785429\ntitle: \"Formation of two methylenedioxy bridges by a Sesamum CYP81Q protein yielding a furofuran lignan, (+)-sesamin.\"\nauthors:\n- Ono E\n- Nakai M\n- Fukui Y\n- Tomimori N\n- Fukuchi-Mizutani M\n- Saito M\n- Satake H\n- Tanaka T\n- Katsuta M\n- Umezawa T\n- Tanaka Y\njournal: Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A\nyear: '2006'\ndoi: 10.1073/pnas.0603865103\nkeywords:\n- Amino Acid Sequence\n- Catalysis\n- \"Cytochrome P-450 Enzyme System/chemistry, genetics, isolation & purification\"\n- Dioxoles\n- Furans/metabolism\n- Gene Expression\n- Gene Expression Profiling\n- Lignans/biosynthesis\n- Molecular Sequence Data\n- \"Plant Proteins/chemistry, genetics, isolation & purification\"\n- \"Sesamum/enzymology, genetics\"\ncontent_type: abstract_only\n---\n\n# Formation of two methylenedioxy bridges by a Sesamum CYP81Q protein yielding a furofuran lignan, (+)-sesamin.\n**Authors:** Ono E, Nakai M, Fukui Y, Tomimori N, Fukuchi-Mizutani M, Saito M, Satake H, Tanaka T, Katsuta M, Umezawa T, Tanaka Y\n**Journal:** Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A (2006)\n**DOI:** [10.1073/pnas.0603865103](https://doi.org/10.1073/pnas.0603865103)\n\n## Content\n\n1. Proc Natl Acad Sci U S A. 2006 Jun 27;103(26):10116-21. doi: \n10.1073/pnas.0603865103. Epub 2006 Jun 19.\n\nFormation of two methylenedioxy bridges by a Sesamum CYP81Q protein yielding a \nfurofuran lignan, (+)-sesamin.\n\nOno E(1), Nakai M, Fukui Y, Tomimori N, Fukuchi-Mizutani M, Saito M, Satake H, \nTanaka T, Katsuta M, Umezawa T, Tanaka Y.\n\nAuthor information:\n(1)Institutes for Advanced Technology, Suntory, 1-1-1 Wakayamadai, \nShimamoto-cho, Mishima, Osaka 618-8503, Japan. eiichiro.ono@suntory.co.jp\n\n(+)-Sesamin, a furofuran class lignan, is widespread in vascular plants and \nrepresented by Sesamum spp. (+)-Sesamin has been of rapidly growing interest \nbecause of its beneficial biological effects in mammals, but its biosynthesis \nand physiological roles in plants remain to be clarified. It is speculated to be \nsynthesized from (+)-pinoresinol by means of (+)-piperitol by formation of two \nmethylenedioxy bridges mediated by two distinct Sesamum indicum cytochrome P450 \n(SiP450) proteins. Here, we report an SiP450, CYP81Q1, that alone catalyzes \n(+)-sesamin biosynthesis from (+)-pinoresinol by means of (+)-piperitol by \nforming two methylenedioxy bridges. The CYP81Q1 gene expression profile was \ntemporally consistent with the accumulation pattern of (+)-sesamin during seed \ndevelopment. The CYP81Q1-GFP chimera protein was colocalized with an endoplasmic \nreticulum (ER)-targeting chimera protein, indicating that (+)-sesamin \nbiosynthesis occurs on the ER cytoplasmic surface. Moreover, we isolated two \nCYP81Q1 homologs from other Sesamum spp. Sesamum radiatum CYP81Q2 showed dual \n(+)-piperitol/(+)-sesamin synthetic activity. CYP81Q2, as well as CYP81Q1, \ntherefore, corresponds to a (+)-piperitol/(+)-sesamin synthase in lignan \nbiosynthesis. In contrast, Sesamum alatum CYP81Q3 showed no activity, in accord \nwith (+)-sesamin being deficient in S. alatum. Our findings not only provide \ninsight into lignan biosynthesis but also unravel a unique mode of cytochrome \nP450 action.\n\nDOI: 10.1073/pnas.0603865103\nPMCID: PMC1502515\nPMID: 16785429 [Indexed for MEDLINE]\n\nConflict of interest statement: Conflict of interest statement: No conflicts \ndeclared.","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
